AGI -&nbsp;The EU Court annulled sanctions in Petr Aven>, with Russian and Latvian citizenship, and Mikhail Fridman>, with Russian and Israeli citizenship, two important members of the Alfa Group, a conglomerate comprising the Alfa Bank, one of the main Russian banks. The decision was "dannosa" by Yulia Navalnaya, widow of Russian opponent Alexei Navalny.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The two entrepreneurs had been included in the blacklist EUe by the Council because they were considered associated with other figures affected by restrictive measures, as well as Vladimir Putin>. According to the Council, they provided material or financial support to Russian decision makers, and supported actions and policies that compromise or threaten territorial integrity, sovereignty and independence of Ukraine. Aven and Fridman instead believe that the evidence provided by the Council is not reliable or credible, and that the assessments of the Council are incorrect.
&nbsp;
The Court of First Instance accepted their appeals and annulled both initial acts and maintenance acts in the lists of persons affected by restrictive measures for the period between 28 February 2022 and 15 March 2023. The Court of First Instance considers that no argument of the grounds contained in the initial proceedings is sufficiently suffraged and that the inclusion of Aven and Fridman in the contested lists was therefore not justified. With regard to maintenance proceedings, the Court of First Instance held that the Council did not provide any further evidence than those on which it was founded in the context of initial acts.
<h2> The reaction of Navalnaya</h2>
"I would like to ask European politicians what has changed since they imposed sanctions on Russian oligarchs," wrote Yulia Navalnaya on X. "No Friedman nor Aven have issued statements against war, nor have they tried to put an end to it," says Navalnaya, who is carrying out her husband's political legacy, "they simply hired very expensive lawyers and found good lobbyists."
&nbsp;
"The Russians against the war in Europe must face many problems, but for the Russian oligarchs everything is easily solved with money," the woman denounces. "This is the third year of war. During this period no specific mechanism emerged to impose sanctions or to get out of it," recalls Navalnaya concluding with a warning: "The decision to revoke sanctions against Fridman and Aven is harmful. This will only weaken the movement against war and help Putin remain in power longer." &nbsp;
<h2> For the Kremlin sanctions were "illegal"</h2>
During the daily press conference, journalists asked the Kremlin spokesman, Dmitry Peskov>, whether the sentence was a positive development and an indication of common sense, or whether it is politically motivated and a response to the position of businessmen. "I think it's neither. Absolutely every case is individual and must be considered separately. Of course, representatives of large companies can contest sanctions against them in the courts and are exploiting these opportunities," Peskov said.
&nbsp;
"In any case, we believe that these sanctions are illegitimate, unjust, destructive and perhaps, in some way, even shameful for the bodies that have approved them," he said.&nbsp;

